<HEADLINE>
FT  19 FEB 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Tomorrow's World provides a timely 'Sport Special' which considers the part
played by science in achieving success, whether by improving the ability of
athletes, their training, psychology, equipment, or what they ingest,
including drugs. The programme highlights the British bobsleigh team which
prepared for the winter Olympics by taking its sledge design and philosophy
from the east Germans (7.30 BBC1).
Bookmark (8.10 BBC2) offers a drama documentary called 'Miss Pym's Day Out'
which re-creates November 23 1977 in the life of novelist Barbara Pym. On
that day she went to the Jubilee bazaar in Finstock and then travelled to
London for the Booker Prize ceremony, her novel 'Quartet In Autumn' having
been shortlisted. Channel 4 begins a series of six 'weekly glimpses' of how
the 6m inhabitants of St Petersburg are surviving their first winter since
the collapse of the USSR. Kevin Sim (who made the excellent documentary
'Four Hours In My Lai') is living in the city, making the programmes there,
and sending them back for sub-titling (9.45). Dispatches is yet another
attempt to whip up interest in satanism (10.30 C4).
</TEXT>
