<HEADLINE>
FT  19 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: Tory school choices highlighted -
Education
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR yesterday attempted to push education up the pre-election agenda by
asking why Tory ministers continued to prefer private schools for their
children in spite of their claims to 'have improved state education out of
all recognition'.
Mr Jack Straw, shadow education secretary, said the entire Labour frontbench
used the state system while only one Cabinet minister - Mr Tony Newton,
social security secretary - sent his children to state secondary schools.
His charges were promptly derided as 'nasty, personalised attacks' by Mr
Kenneth Clarke, education secretary, who claimed they showed that Labour did
not have an education policy.
'The point of our reforms is to raise standards in state schools so that no
parents should feel obliged to send their children to private schools unless
they wish to,' Mr Clarke said.
Mr Straw insisted that the fact that ministers still opted for private
schools was eloquent testimony to their lack of confidence in state
education, in spite of 13 years of Tory government.
This point, he added, was first made in a 1990 pamphlet by Mr George Walden,
Tory MP for Buckingham and a former education minister. Asking why ministers
avoided the state sector, Mr Walden concluded: 'The only answer now is the
truth, and the truth is scarcely sayable by any government minister.'
Mr Straw said that the election would give voters the choice between a
Labour Cabinet who used state schools and 'a Conservative party who have no
personal interest in state education'.
He went on to produce new Labour research showing that nearly all cabinet
ministers in Germany and France used publicly funded schools.
Asked whether he was dragging personal issues into the election, Mr Straw
insisted he had taken care not to identify individual Cabinet ministers'
children or their schools.
'What I was articulating was a profound question about this government's
commitment to state education first raised by a Tory MP,' he said.
</TEXT>
