<HEADLINE>
FT  19 FEB 92 / City Challenge to be given further Pounds 750m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR MICHAEL HESELTINE, environment secretary, took the election campaign to
Labour's heartlands yesterday when he pledged Pounds 750m for urban renewal
to 20 inner-city areas under the second phase of the government's City
Challenge scheme.
All of England's 57 urban priority areas (UPAs) - including the 11 which
were successful in last year's pilot competition - are free to bid for the
funds. Each winner will receive Pounds 37.5m spread over five years from
1993-94.
The 57 areas - with average unemployment rates of more than 12.5 per cent -
are concentrated in London, the north, the north-west and the Yorkshire and
Humberside region. Bids for funds must include a scheme from councils for
improving a run-down area in partnership with local businesses, voluntary
groups and community organisations.
The Pounds 750m is not new money. As with the Pounds 412m allocated in the
first phase, it will be taken from the government's existing urban
programmes. Funding for the two phases combined will consume about a fifth
of the budget allocation for the four main urban programmes - with serious
implications for councils unsuccessful in the bidding.
Mr Heseltine said: 'City Challenge is about vision, quality, partnership and
expecting local authorities to lead their communities.' To be successful,
bids would need to exhibit 'flair and imagination', and the capacity to
attract private-sector investment, he added.
Mr David Blunkett, Labour's local government spokesman, said the government
was 'playing games' with inner cities. 'Those authorities who lose will have
wasted time and very scarce resources,' he said.
Mr Jeremy Beecham, leader of Newcastle upon Tyne City Council and chairman
of the Labour-led Association of Metropolitan Authorities, condemned the
principle of bidding, but was 'pleased that all UPAs will be able to
compete'.
In addition to yesterday's launch in London, ministers are planning
'regional seminars' to publicise City Challenge. Councils must declare their
intention to bid for second-phase funding by the end of the month. They must
then submit a full proposal by April 22.
If the government is re-elected, it intends to pick the winners by the end
of July. If Labour takes office, Mr Bryan Gould, shadow environment
secretary, has pledged that it will meet funding commitments already agreed,
but will then integrate City Challenge into a single urban programme to be
distributed on the basis of need.
</TEXT>
