<HEADLINE>
FT  19 FEB 92 / Warning of 'chaos' over council tax
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COUNCIL TAX could produce as much administrative chaos as poll tax unless it
is changed significantly, the National Association of Citizens' Advice
Bureaux (Nacab) warned yesterday.
Nacab says in a report comparing plans for council tax with its experience
of poll tax that clear information about the operation of the new tax should
be made available well before its introduction. Nacab also wants an option
for taxpayers to pay weekly, and says they should be allowed to pay any
council-tax debts by 'realistic instalments' before bailiffs are called in.
Nacab adds that much tighter regulation of bailiffs is needed.
The 456 Citizens' Advice Bureaux are still dealing with 14,000 queries a
month about poll tax, also called the community charge, and Nacab recommends
100 per cent poll-tax rebates for those on low incomes compared with the
present 80 per cent ceiling.
Ms Ann Abraham, Nacab chief executive, said: 'From registration right
through to arrears and enforcement, bureaux all over the country have seen
thousands of people in difficulties over paying their community charge. The
government is in danger of making the same mistakes with the council tax.'
Charging Into The Tax. Nacab, 115 Pentonville Road, London N1 9LZ. Pounds 5.
</TEXT>
