<HEADLINE>
FT  19 FEB 92 / BR may relaunch promotion for east coast line
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH RAIL is considering a marketing relaunch of its showpiece east coast
main line to Scotland in an effort to tempt back customers irritated by the
problems which have dogged the route since its Pounds 500m electrification
was completed last summer.
Vandalism and technical difficulties have affected the performance of the
line - which links London with York, Newcastle upon Tyne and Edinburgh -
since it became fully electrified in July. This has frustrated BR's hopes
that faster journey times would allow it to compete more effectively for the
business and leisure markets.
The line's high-speed trains were the centrepiece of InterCity's promotion
last autumn.
The marketing drive was backed by a promotion, billed as the world's biggest
travel offer, in which InterCity offered free travel worth about Pounds 50m
in exchange for vouchers given to shoppers at Boots stores. Allied to this
was extensive publicity in northern England and Scotland.
But yesterday Mr Philip Benham, BR's customer service and retail manager for
the InterCity east coast line, said BR was considering a campaign to
persuade potential customers that the line's difficulties had been
surmounted.
'We're thinking quite seriously at the moment about how to relaunch our
marketing effort and how best to target it,' said Mr Benham. 'We have quite
a task on our hands to regain confidence.'
BR is today running one of its Q-trains, a special anti-vandal train manned
by British Transport Police, in Teesside. A similar Q-train, the first on
the east coast line since electrification, travelled around Tyneside last
week. The purpose of the train is partly to catch vandals and partly to
impress on the public that BR is tackling the problem.
Mr Benham said the line's difficulties had been caused partly by 'teething
problems' as staff became used to new technology. There had also been
serious vandalism including repeated damage to the fibre-optic cable which
controls signalling and points and carries BR's internal telecommunication
links.
</TEXT>
