<HEADLINE>
FT  19 FEB 92 / UK News (Employment): Social workers lose jobs after long
strike
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MORE than 100 employees of Camden council in north London yesterday lost
their jobs as social workers following a long-running strike.
The striking social workers, all members of the Nalgo public-sector union,
will be considered for other jobs within the council over the next four
weeks. But Camden said they were unlikely to secure jobs within the
authority because of cost-cutting and would probably be made redundant.
Nalgo yesterday accused Camden of trying to escalate the dispute and said it
planned to ask other council staff to strike in support of the social
workers.
The union plans to extend an existing ban on Nalgo members applying for
social work posts in Camden to all social services posts.
The strike, which has lasted nearly 10 months, started after the council
refused to pay a nationally negotiated increase in 1989. Camden had
previously negotiated a local increase to boost recruitment. Staff then went
on strike in April last year .
Mr Phil Turner, who heads the staff and management services committee, said
the national agreement did not apply because the local agreement 'offered
better terms'.
He said the council had offered conciliation and arbitration, which was
rejected by Nalgo and the social workers.
The council said it has been forced to restructure the social work
department because of recent legislation. Before Christmas last year, social
workers were offered new posts and a pay rise. The deadline for acceptance
was yesterday.
</TEXT>
