</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
MR ALBERT REYNOLDS, the new prime minister of the Irish Republic, is to meet
Mr John Major, the UK premier, in London next week for talks about Northern
Ireland.
Mr Reynolds yesterday told his parliament that the planned meeting had been
brought forward because of the 'changed situation' in Ulster. It is
scheduled for next Wednesday.
The Irish prime minister said that after a meeting between Mr Charles
Haughey, Mr Reynolds' predecessor, and Mr Major in Dublin last December, it
was agreed to hold prime ministerial meetings every six months. But
following recent telephone calls with Mr Major about the continuing spiral
of violence in Ulster, that schedule was revised.
Mr Reynolds said that his government was ready to do 'everything possible'
to help parties in Ulster resume dialogue abandoned last summer.
