<HEADLINE>
FT  19 FEB 92 / Air 2000 to lease four Airbus A320s
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SECOND UK charter airline has decided to operate Airbus A320 narrow-body
airliners, whose sophisticated computerised control systems have recently
been under criticism.
This followed the crash of a French Air Inter A320 last month near
Strasbourg, killing 87 people.
Air 2000, the charter airline of the Owners Abroad tour group, said
yesterday it would lease four new A320s from ORIX Aviation Systems of
Dublin. The aircraft will be powered by V2500 engines built by the IAE
consortium which includes Rolls-Royce, Pratt &amp; Whitney of the US, MTU of
Germany and a group of Japanese aero-engine companies.
The first two aircraft will be delivered to Air 2000 for use this summer and
the other two will enter service next year.
Last month Excalibur, a new UK charter airline, announced orders for three
A320s.
Air 2000 now operates a fleet of Boeing 757 twin-engine aircraft. It said
the A320s would meet a need for a smaller airliner to operate from
provincial airports and on less dense routes.
Meanwhile London City Airport received a boost yesterday with the
announcement that CityAir Scandinavia, a new Swedish airline, plans to
introduce daily services using British Aerospace 146 jets between Stockholm
and London.
This follows the extension of the Docklands airport runway to enable BAe 146
jets to operate there. Crossair, the regional carrier which is 51 per cent
owned by Swissair, has already announced daily services between Zurich and
London City using BAe 146s.
CityAir Scandinavia is absorbing Malmo Aviation, a carrier that operates
passenger services on the Malmo-London Gatwick and Malmo-Hanburg routes as
well as cargo services for TNT, the Australian transport group.
The airline said it intended to start a twice-daily service between
Stockholm and London City 'as soon as is practical after the official
opening of the airport's extended runway on March 30'.
Ryanair, the independent Irish carrier, is expanding its flights from London
Stansted to Ireland with a daily service to Shannon from April 10. The route
is already operated by Aer Lingus, the Irish flag carrier.
</TEXT>
