<HEADLINE>
FT  19 FEB 92 / Red tape cuts to be accelerated
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL, Business Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
REGULATIONS on betting shops, employment agencies, licensed taxis and some
professional partnerships could be revised or abandoned under the
government's initiative to cut the red tape surrounding British businesses.
Mr John Redwood, corporate affairs minister, yesterday reported on progress
to reduce the 'irksome burdens' on business and set out plans to step up
deregulation over the next year.
He said the Home Office was considering if betting shops should be allowed
to open late to reflect the increase in evening race meetings. Licensing
controls on taxis and other passenger-hire vehicles were being reviewed by
the Department of Transport to establish if they were unnecessarily
restrictive.
Mr Redwood said the Department of Trade and Industry also intended to ease
restrictions on the size of large partnerships offering a mix of
professional disciplines.
On a broader front, Mr Redwood said businesses had been relieved of 163
forms and guidance documents in the past 12 months. As part of the
initiative, government departments had also identified 20 of more than 400
types of business licences which they intended to scrap during the coming
year. Mr Redwood said the thrust to eliminate outdated and often costly
regulatory measures was being targeted partially at Brussels, which produced
many regulations and directives affecting business. He said the British
government intended to oversee 'a deregulatory presidency', particularly in
respect of the single market, when it assumed the EC presidency in the
summer.
The minister stressed that government departments were also examining ways
of reducing the statistical burden on industry and commerce. Local
authorities were being encouraged to examine the necessity of regulations
and to ensure enforcement was consistent.
Mr Redwood said the government was particularly concerned to ease the burden
for small businesses. Increasing numbers of companies could now make much
simplified tax returns, and a review was under way to see if audit and
accounting requirements for very small businesses could also be reduced.
Mr Peter Lilley, trade and industry secretary, yesterday announced a scheme
to bring senior academics into industry for up to six months to work on
technology projects.
</TEXT>
