<HEADLINE>
FT  19 FEB 92 / Chinese leader presses for faster reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON HOLBERTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HONG KONG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SIGNALS that 1992 will see economic and possibly political reform in China
strengthened yesterday when a pro-Beijing newspaper in Hong Kong again
referred to calls by the paramount leader, Deng Xiaoping for accelerated
reform, Simon Holberton reports from Hong Kong.
Wen Wei Po said government departments had been circulating Deng's
observations on his recent visit to southern China - the region which has
most embraced economic reform.
Diplomats and analysts said the article was significant because the
dissemination of information in this way was part of the Chinese way of
building consensus about policy. It follows several reports which taken
together suggest a struggle for party policy and succession is under way.
However, not all accept that recent developments heralded a return to
reform. Professor David Shambaugh of London's School of Oriental and African
Studies, said a year ago the Chinese press ran pro-reform articles only for
hardliners to reassert themselves later.
The Chinese communist party is due to convene its 14th party congress late
this year. At this meeting the party's 'line', or policy, will be
established and a leadership appointed to carry it through. Signs of change
may be visible at a meeting of the National People's Congress, China's token
parliament, when it convenes in late March.
Wen Wei Po said Deng's view was the improvement of the economy should be the
Communist party's first priority in contrast to party dogma which since
Tiananmen square has stressed correct ideological thinking.
</TEXT>
