<HEADLINE>
FT  18 FEB 92 / UK Company News: Assistance for Maxwell pensioners kept to
minimum
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT is not prepared to do more than meet its statutory
requirement to pay the state guaranteed minimum pension to members of the
various Maxwell company pension schemes, Mr Tony Newton, social security
secretary, told a Commons select committee.
Mr Newton said he and representatives of the Department of Trade and
Industry and the Treasury met 10 days ago with trustees and administrators
of the Maxwell schemes and told them that pensioners would receive the
guaranteed minimum if pension fund assets had disappeared.
'I don't see a possibility of going beyond that,' he said.
He added neither the trustees of Mirror Group Newspapers nor the
administrators of Maxwell Communication Corporation had discussed their
plans to wind up their respective schemes. 'Those concerned had a divided
opinion on the effects of winding up.'
Last Friday, MGN announced it would wind up its existing pension scheme and
begin a new one, paving the way for the government to supplement the fund by
providing the guaranteed minimum for members.
Meanwhile, Mr Newton ducked MPs' questions about the type of pension law
reform - if any - under consideration by the government. 'The government's
position is that we need to see the report of the Serious Fraud Office
before we can decide what issues need to be addressed, he said.
Separately, Mr Newton said that the Department of Social Security and the
Occupational Pensions Board were preparing rules to improve the information
which must be disclosed to pension fund members.
