<HEADLINE>
FT  18 FEB 92 / UK and EC settle Pounds 120m funding dispute
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS and DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE UK government yesterday settled a long-running dispute with the European
Commission which had blocked the release of about Pounds 120m in European
Community funds for Britain's depressed coal-mining regions.
Mr Peter Lilley, Britain's trade and industry secretary, said the government
had agreed to introduce more 'transparency' into the way it accounted for
funds distributed by the European Regional Development Fund.
He told MPs that the government planned also to widen 'competition' by
allowing agencies such as British Coal Enterprises, urban development
corporations and regional development agencies to compete against local
authorities for the EC funds.
Mr Bruce Millan, EC commissioner for regional policy, stressed yesterday
that the agreement with the British government required that EC regional
grants would be 'identified separately in expenditure programmes, and public
expenditure cover (from the UK side) will automatically be made available
for them'.
Mr Millan claimed the 'automatic' nature of this matching finance was
missing from yesterday's statement by Mr Lilley. He said the agreement they
had reached was 'very clear' and he hoped the government would abide by it
honestly. The deal, described by the Labour party as a 'humiliating
climbdown', will allow the immediate distribution of Pounds 115m from the
Community's Rechar programme to fund more than 50 projects in areas hit by
coal-mine closures. Scotland, Lancashire and Nottinghamshire are among the
main beneficiaries.
The agreement should also allow the Commission to lift a threatened block on
up to Pounds 900m of regional funds for 1992-93 for a range of projects in
depressed areas.
The dispute, the subject of fierce political exchanges at Westminster in
recent months, arose after Mr Millan demanded changes to ensure that money
allocated to Britain would represent a clear 'addition' to normal Treasury
spending and that the EC money would reach the industrially-stricken regions
at which it was targeted.
The stance taken by Brussels sparked sharp differences within the cabinet,
with Mr Michael Heseltine, the environment secretary, privately taking the
Commission's side.
Mr Lilley and the Treasury initially opposed any change in the way the EC
funds were included in the government's overall public-spending totals. But
Conservative MPs in areas denied the blocked funds had been pressing for a
settlement before the general election.
</TEXT>
