<HEADLINE>
FT  18 FEB 92 / UK News (Employment): Skilled blue-collar workers 'winning
big rises'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SKILLED blue-collar workers are receiving pay increases well above the rate
of inflation because employers fear skill shortages when the recession ends,
according to a survey of operative and clerical pay rates, Diane Summers
writes.
Increases averaged 9.3 per cent last year for blue-collar workers in
administration, catering, distribution, engineering, personnel and
production, according to the survey of more than 1,000 companies carried out
by Reward, the pay research group.
The report says skilled workers are being looked after well by their
employers. 'Employers appear to be saying 'those we keep, we will pay well
to ensure that the organisation does not stall its growth when the recession
ends'.'
Examples of big rises include: 17.7 per cent for warehouse supervisors and
15.4 per cent for skilled warehouse staff; 22.5 per cent for driver/packers;
16.2 per cent for some grades of skilled craft workers; 21.2 per cent for
semi-skilled plant maintenance workers and 12.7 for production supervisors.
Clerical pay has risen less sharply, with an average rise of 6.6 per cent.
Reward forecasts a steady decline in pay increases for clerical staff over
the coming months, with an average of 5 per cent until September this year.
Central London clerical pay remains the highest in the country at 41.4 per
cent more than the average. South Wales is lowest, where clerical pay is
14.2 per cent less than the average.
Clerical and Operative Rewards, January 1992. Reward, Diamond Way, Stone
Business Park, Stone, Staffordshire ST15 OSD. Pounds 100.
</TEXT>
