<HEADLINE>
FT  18 FEB 92 / UK News (Employment): Stationery Office unions urge
rejection of 3.5% offer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WORKERS at Her Majesty's Stationery Office are being urged to take
industrial action over pay just a year after HMSO became the first Civil
Service agency to break away from national pay bargaining.
Four unions have recommended that the 2,000 non-industrial civil servants at
HMSO reject the proposed deal, which they estimate is worth 3.5 per cent
from the settlement date of last October.
Two, the NUCPS and CPSA, are urging industrial action short of a strike.
The other two, the IPMS and GMPU, say they will follow suit if their members
reject the deal.
Action the unions are considering includes working to rule or to job
description and an overtime ban. They are also considering strikes by
selected groups of workers.
Mr Graeme Watt, NUCPS assistant secretary, said any action would probably
delay supplies to customers.
The offer compares with rises of at least 6.5 per cent last year for civil
servants who remain in national bargaining. Last week workers whose pay is
determined by public-sector pay review bodies were awarded rises averaging
6.5 per cent.
The dispute at HMSO is likely to strengthen the resolve of Civil Service
unions in maintaining national bargaining arrangements.
The government is urging greater devolution of pay determination as part of
its Citizen's Charter programme.
The unions ordered the ballots after failing to persuade HMSO to ask the
Treasury to vary its Pounds 4m profit target for last year.
HMSO managers had argued that they were unable to pay more than the offer
because anything greater would have jeopardised the Pounds 4m target. They
offered a three-month pay deferral followed by a 4.7 per cent increase for
the rest of the pay year.
Union leaders are concerned that similar arguments will be used in the pay
negotiations next year, especially as the profit target has been increased
to Pounds 6m for the 1992 calendar year.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 13
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-8309</DOCNO>
