<HEADLINE>
FT  18 FEB 92 / UK News (Employment): Industrial action threat at BP plants
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SHOP STEWARDS at BP Chemicals' three main UK plants threatened industrial
action yesterday over the company's decision to withdraw collective
bargaining rights at the Baglan Bay plant in south Wales.
But union representatives at Baglan Bay, Hull and Grangemouth, near Falkirk,
decided to advise Baglan Bay members to accede to the company's request to
sign personal contracts.
Mr Fred Higgs, national secretary of the TGWU general union, said the advice
to sign was intended to stop divisions among workers as some union members
had already signed under threat of redundancy.
'The shop stewards decided that members at the three sites would be urged to
take industrial action if the company does not remove the personal contracts
and if its executives refuse to meet national officials over the issue.'
BP Chemicals told the TGWU and the AEU engineering workers' union last week
that it was giving 90 days notice of the end of collective pay agreements at
Baglan Bay.
</TEXT>
