<DATE>920218
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  18 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics (Campaign Profile): A gentleman in a
streetfighter's world
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR DONALD DEWAR is a rare example of a politician who gives the profession a
good name. That, of course, is what his more combative colleagues single out
as his principal weakness.
The gangling, 54-year-old shadow Scottish secretary is widely respected on
both sides of the Commons for all-round integrity and scrupulous
reasonableness. Perhaps, too much so.
Such traits are unusual enough in the Commons. They are all the more so in
the rough world of Scottish politics, where quiet diplomacy is often
reinforced by the unspoken threat of a well-aimed kick.
With his countrymen once again in turmoil over devolution and independence,
Mr Dewar is arguably Labour's most embattled politician - after Mr Neil
Kinnock himself.
If the party fails to win the coming election it will be up to Mr Dewar to
prevent a split in his party that could dash its chances of ever forming an
administration in Westminster.
With an iron grip on Scottish local government and 48 of the country's 72
parliamentary seats, it is a wonder that any Labour leader in Scotland will
be able to justify being denied power by the very Act of Union the party is
pledged to defend.
It is after the election and not before that he may face his most serious
political test.
In recent weeks, however, Mr Dewar has suffered his toughest trial since the
Scottish National party converted a 19,500 Labour majority into a 3,500
nationalist victory at the 1988 Govan by-election.
With a general election likely for April 9, he has faced unaccustomed
criticism for what was widely seen as a lacklustre performance in a
televised debate on Scotland's mounting constitutional controversy.
Days later an opinion poll showed a surge in nationalist support with a
remarkable 50 per cent of Scots preferring outright independence to Labour's
alternative plan for a Scottish parliament.
On February 4 Mr Dewar acted to calm anxiety among Scottish MPs as they
gathered for their regular monthly meeting in parliament.
Before anyone could voice unease he defused the concern with a disarmingly
contrite critique of his own performance and agreement that Labour should
now sell its devolution policy under the more positive banner of 'home
rule'.
Furthermore, he accepted that he would devolve more campaigning roles to his
troops. One MP commented afterwards: 'It was a typically robust performance
by Donald and everyone went away satisfied.' But Mr Dewar's emollient style
is beginning to worry a few. As one leftwing backbencher put it: 'Donald's a
good Glasgow University debater, but he's no street-fighter.'
Mr George Foulkes, a friend and admirer of Mr Dewar - like the vast majority
of Scots Labour MPs - puts it more gently: 'He is sometimes too reasonable
and tends to see the other side of arguments. That can be dangerous,
especially so close to an election.'
A scion of Glasgow's professional classes, Donald Campbell Dewar is a
typical Scottish Labour laird and a prime example of the party's
academicly-inclined, legally-trained oligarchy. The only child of a doctor,
he was sent to that stiflingly conservative bulwark of respectability, the
Glasgow Academy.
At Glasgow University the 'Gannet', as he was nicknamed, leapt to prominence
when he succeeded Mr John Smith as leader of the Labour club. It was here he
first encountered his hero, the late Hugh Gaitskell.
After qualifying as a lawyer he prised Aberdeen South from the Tories in
1966, completing his philosophical apprenticeship as parliamentary private
secretary to Mr Tony Crosland, then president of the Board of Trade.
An eight-year exile from the Commons ended in 1978 when he narrowly held
Glasgow's Garscadden constituency at a by-election, in spite of a fierce
challenge from the SNP. Today he has a 19,000 majority.
Always a devolutionist, Mr Dewar's enthusiasm for Scottish culture has been
fed by a passion for collecting well-bound volumes of 18th century Scots
literature, so chaotically scattered round his home that it was once taken
as evidence of a burglary.
His ectomorphic form, vast appetite, rapid-fire speaking style and public
gregariousness hides a self-deprecating personality and a manic
preoccupation with work that prompt some to conclude that he is motivated
more by some unexplained inner despair than a passion for social reform.
'Donald is never happier than when he is miserable,' is an observation that
has become a cliche.
If Mr Dewar's networking has proved crucial in keeping the potentially
faction-ridden Scottish party united, so too has his extreme caution - which
has led crueller critics to accuse him of being more calculating civil
servant than vision-driven politician.
In particular, they point to the Scottish Labour leadership's hovering too
long on the fringes of the Scottish convention - the body that first
brokered the current round of devolutionist thinking.
Others say that Mr Dewar, and Mr Murray Elder, the Scottish regional
secretary, have been over-zealous in their management of the party,
confining strategic decision-making to an elite inner circle.
Another Dewar virtue turned vice is his strong personal loyalty - an example
is his support for less admired frontbench colleagues like Mr Tony
Worthington - which is widely deemed to betray a lack of ruthlessness
bordering on the unprofessional.
But the most damaging charge in the radical atmosphere now prevailing in
Scotland is that Mr Dewar is essentially an establishment figure, looking
forward to playing Westminster's viceroy in its northern colony. It is a
card the nationalists are certain to play.
Mr Dewar is fond of saying that being Scottish secretary - with powers drawn
from seven or eight English departments of state - is his greatest ambition.
With Scotland in its current fever it would be politically much cannier,
perhaps, to hint that he would prefer to crown his career as prime minister
of a Scottish parliament - even, indeed, if that is not entirely true.
It is typical of Mr Dewar's guileless honesty, if not his political nous,
that he would not dream of doing so.
</TEXT>
