<HEADLINE>
FT  18 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: Opposition launches NHS offensive -
Pre-election campaign
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS and ALAN PIKE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LIBERAL Democrats yesterday backed guaranteed 'sustained increases' in
National Health Service funding, as Labour accused the government of
creating a US-style, two-tier health service.
NHS spending would be increased in real terms every year if the Liberal
Democrats' policy document were implemented. Mr Paddy Ashdown, Liberal
Democrat leader, said service levels would remain constant, or rise, after
taking account of demographic changes and higher costs.
A fully-costed programme will be given in the party's election manifesto.
The final, pre-election version of Labour's health policy will be launched
by Mr Neil Kinnock, party leader, and Mr Robin Cook, shadow health
secretary, on Thursday. Mr Cook prefaced the launch yesterday by producing a
dossier of case studies which he said showed that patients were being forced
to go to the private sector for treatment - in effect, 'privatising' the
NHS.
The Labour proposals will pledge the party to ending the internal market on
which the government's NHS reforms of last year are based. This will include
an undertaking to abolish the two most highly publicised aspects of the
reforms - self-governing trust hospitals and GP fund-holders. The proposals
will, however, recognise the case for giving GPs greater involvement in
planning.
Labour leaders acknowledge the need to keep purchasing and provision of
health care separate - an approach which is being adopted in health systems
around the world. They believe it can be achieved managerially in health
authorities, rather than by market mechanisms.
The Liberal Democrat proposals also embrace the separation of responsibility
between deciding priorities and running services, but they would be based on
service agreements between democratically accountable health authorities and
hospitals.
The party also plans to abolish charges for eye and dental checks, increase
investment and gradually reduce prescription charges. Tobacco promotion
would be banned.
Mrs Virginia Bottomley, health minister, said that whereas in 1987 the then
Alliance parties had backed an 'internal market', the Liberal Democrats were
now 'desperately in search of a workable health policy'. She added: 'This
isn't it.'
Mr Ashdown said yesterday that Labour or the Tories should try to form a
coalition government with minority parties in the event of a hung
parliament, rather than making a 'fast dash' to a second contest. 'The
voters want a constructive, more positive approach from their politicians,'
he said.
</TEXT>
