<HEADLINE>
FT  18 FEB 92 / Effluent charges to rise 20%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN HUNT, Environment Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THOUSANDS of industrial groups, water companies and farmers face a 20 per
cent rise in fees for discharging effluent into rivers and coastal waters
from April.
The polluting effluent comes from industrial plants, sewage treatment works
and discharges from some farms.
The increased charges, announced yesterday by Mr David Trippier, environment
minister, are part of the 'polluter pays' principle, and are intended to
cover the cost of pollution control administered by the National Rivers
Authority.
The total revenue the rivers watchdog receives from administering licenses
and monitoring discharges will rise by Pounds 2m to Pounds 38m. It will also
receive a government grant of Pounds 81.8m for pollution control during the
coming year. It will be able to spend 15 per cent more on pollution control
than in the current year.
There are more than 86,000 licenses granted by the authority to allow
discharges.
</TEXT>
