<HEADLINE>
FT  18 FEB 92 / Wakeham seeks coal power deal
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN Wakeham, the energy secretary, is trying to persuade electricity
suppliers to buy enough coal-fired electricity from generators to guarantee
sales of 40m tonnes from British Coal's deep mines, according to Coal UK,
the newsletter published today.
The deal would mean that British Coal could sell a further 20m tonnes of
cheaper coal from surface mines, giving it sales close to the 65m tonnes it
presently sells to the electricity industry.
Although reports that Mr Wakeham was working hard to secure a contract
between British Coal and the electricity industry surfaced last week, it is
still unclear whether the regional electricity companies will accept Mr
Wakeham's proposal. If the proposal is accepted, it would compel the
generators, National Power and PowerGen, to buy from British Coal to supply
the regional companies.
The deal is thought to offer British Coal Pounds 35 a tonne, compared with
more than Pounds 42 a tonne at present. This would allow it to keep open 28
pits it identified as most economic.
</TEXT>
