<HEADLINE>
FT  18 FEB 92 / Minister announces curb on investment by pension funds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EMPLOYER-RELATED investment by occupational pension schemes will be limited
from March 9 to 5 per cent of funds, the Department of Social Security
announced yesterday. New regulations will also mean that self-investment
below that level will have to be disclosed.
A ceiling on self-investment was called for in the Social Security Act 1990.
But it did not take effect because the government could not agree on how to
define self-investment or where to impose a ceiling. The National
Association of Pension Funds, the industry body, had urged a complete ban on
employer-related investment by pension funds. The rules do not apply to
small self-administered schemes with fewer than 12 members, or to
employer-related investments in bank or building society accounts.
The issue is controversial because pension funds have often invested in
shares in the companies which employ their members and in assets owned by
the companies. Thus, if the employing company collapsed, workers might lose
much of their pensions as well as their jobs.
The rules announced yesterday will not force pension funds to sell property
they own which is used by the employer. However, if such property already
exceeds 5 per cent of all investments, they will not be able to buy more.
The rules bar investment in the employing company an loans or securities
issued to or by 'any person who is connected with, or an associate of, the
employer.' However, Mr Tony Newton, social security secretary, rejected a
request from the Occupational Pensions Board to define more clearly who is a
connected or associated person or company.
It is not clear whether some of the investments made by the late Robert
Maxwell's pension funds in companies in which Maxwell was building a
personal stake would have fallen foul of the new rules.
Assistance for Maxwell pensioners, Page 24
</TEXT>
