FT  18 FEB 92 / Big energy users seek nuclear cap
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIET SYCHRAVA
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LARGE consumers of electricity will today ask Mr John Wakeham, the energy
secretary, to cut their bills by capping the subsidy they pay to the nuclear
industry.
A group of large customers, including Blue Circle Cement and United
Engineering Steel, has already threatened to stop paying the subsidy, which
represents 11 per cent of their electricity bills, in April.
The Major Energy Users Council is meeting Mr Wakeham in the first of a
series of talks intended to resolve the row over the rise in large
consumers' bills since the electricity industry was privatised in 1990.
Council representatives said that capping the subsidy was one way of getting
bills down to the level enjoyed by their European competitors.
The large users indicated that refusing to pay the levy was a tactic to show
they believed that the government, which collects the levy, was to blame for
the high bills, rather than the generators.
Council members said the group was disturbed that the price at which Nuclear
Electric was offering power - about 2.6p a unit - was being used by National
Power and PowerGen as a benchmark to determine the price at which they would
sell to large users.
