<HEADLINE>
FT  18 FEB 92 / FT Cable and Satellite Conference: EC fears row over sports
rights
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRESSURE is likely to mount on the European Community in the wake of the
winter Olympic games to legislate on the issue of exclusive television
rights to sporting events, a European commissioner warned yesterday.
There have been protests about the exclusive television rights to both the
winter and summer Olympics bought by the European Broadcasting Union, and
about the subsequent sale of exclusive satellite rights to Eurosport, which
consists of a number of broadcasting union members.
Mr Jean Dondelinger, the EC commissioner responsible for audio-visual
policy, told the Financial Times Cable and Satellite Conference in London
yesterday the present approach was 'clearly not the right way' to serve the
market.
The commission had been reluctant to intervene immediately under competition
rules and possibly interfere with programmes. 'What appears to be clear is
that in future the question of access (to rights) still needs a solution,'
said Mr Dondelinger, adding that possible legislation would be considered
later this year.
Mr Dondelinger was answering questions after emphasising that the challenges
posed by the development of high-definition television in Europe were as
great for programme-makers as for equipment manufacturers. 'What the viewer
will want is high quality wide-screen programmes on wide-screen sets,' Mr
Dondelinger said. 'One without the other would be waste of time, effort and
money.'
He also argued that as demand for satellite television increased, the best
possible management of the orbital positions of satellites would be needed
to ensure that viewers received the best pictures and sound at the best
prices.
Mr Jean Grenier, director-general of Eutelsat, the European satellite
organisation, said it planned to locate two satellites in the same orbit.
This meant that about 40 channels could be received with a single dish from
the same orbital position.
The decision, likely to be taken soon, is a clear sign that Eutelsat is
fighting back against the Astra television system. Astra plans to offer 48
channels on a single dish by locating three satellites in virtually the same
orbital position.
Mr Grenier said tests on interference between the two satellite systems
showed that British Sky Broadcasting channels, in which Pearson, publishers
of the Financial Times has a stake, would not be affected by interference as
Astra had previously feared.
Eutelsat still believed, however, that while 60cm satellite dishes could be
used in certain conditions, 80cm dishes were needed to protect against all
risk of interference.
Mr Gerard Le Febvre, director of strategy at CLT, the Luxembourg-based
broadcaster, said that since 1987 the total audience share of public-service
broadcasters in Europe had declined 62 per cent to 35 per cent last year. A
new role for some public-service broadcasters would be to broadcast new
services worldwide via satellite.
Mr Le Febvre said that cable would be the biggest television growth area in
the 1990s. He predicted that in each country there would only be one
national public-service channel with one or two competing pay channels, up
to three private general-interest channels in each language area and a
growing number of special-interest satellite channels.
</TEXT>
