<HEADLINE>
FT  18 FEB 92 / Arthur Young is fined Pounds 100,000 by regulator
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ARTHUR YOUNG, the accountancy firm, was yesterday fined Pounds 100,000 by
its regulatory body for failing to highlight 'seriously misleading' figures
in the 1984 accounts of Milbury, the collapsed house-building group
controlled by Mr Jim Raper.
The penalty is the largest yet imposed through the Joint Disciplinary
Scheme, the self-regulatory mechanism of the institutes of chartered
accountants in England, Wales and Scotland, and the Association of Certified
Accountants.
A committee of inquiry set up under the disciplinary scheme said Arthur
Young, which is now part of Ernst &amp; Young, 'fell below the standard which
should be displayed by, and which may reasonably be expected of, a firm of
chartered accountants serving as auditors of a public company'.
Mr David Brierley and Mr Christopher Wilson, two directors of Milbury who
are chartered accountants, were also 'admonished' by the committee, which
launched its inquiry after a critical report by the Department of Trade and
Industry on the company was published in 1988.
Milbury collapsed in 1985 leaving Pounds 15m owing to creditors after
issuing annual accounts for 1984 which showed pre-tax profits of Pounds
2.1m, and interim results which referred to increased operating profits and
favourable expectations.
The DTI criticised the Stock Exchange, Arthur Young and individuals
associated with the company. Its report said Mr Raper was 'a devious man
(whose) motivation is out-and-out self-interest'.
Arthur Young was accused by the DTI of failing to ensure that Milbury's
accounts complied with accounting standards, with the result that its
profits were 'materially inflated'.
The disciplinary scheme concluded that the treatment of an acquisition and
loans held by the company breached accepted accounting standards; that
policies for interest and advertising costs were 'inappropriate and
imprudent'; and that the 1984 annual report gave a misleading impression of
cash balances.
It added that it had 'taken account of the absence of any acknowledgement by
Arthur Young of their failings during the committee's inquiries'.
Arthur Young has also been asked to contribute Pounds 40,000 towards the
costs of the proceedings. Although it no longer exists, its partners at the
time of the final audit remain liable.
Mr Elwyn Eilledge, senior partner at Ernst &amp; Young who was not connected
with the former Arthur Young, said yesterday he was 'clearly disappointed'.
The firm would probably pay the fine but, he added, 'we believe the accounts
did give a true and fair view at the time.'
</TEXT>
