<HEADLINE>
FT  18 FEB 92 / Garcia is chosen as party chief
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SALLY BOWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PERU'S former president, Mr Alan Garca, has been elected head of the
country's biggest political party, the American Popular Revolutionary
Alliance (Apra), only weeks after being cleared of charges of illegal
personal enrichment while in office.
Mr Garca, who led an Apra administration from 1985-90, was elected secretary
general by popular acclaim during the party's annual congress at the weekend
in the northern city of Trujillo.
The delegates' choice put an end to the ambitions of Mr Luis Alva Castro, Mr
Garca's chief rival, within the party. He has been secretary general for the
past three years.
By threatening not to accept the offered position unless his conditions were
met, Mr Garca succeeded in placing his own candidates in key party
positions. Senator Mercedes Cabanillas becomes his second-in-command and Mr
Abel Salinas, senator and former economy minister, the secretary for
planning.
In December a supreme court judge decided there was insufficient evidence to
proceed with charges that Mr Garca illegally enriched himself during his 12
years in public life, particularly during his presidency.
Mr Garca vehemently denied the charges.
But there was concern in some Apra circles that Mr Garca's choice of Mr
Agustin Mantilla, former interior minister, for the position of
'organisation secretary' would lead to the militarisation of the Apra party.
Apra remains the largest party.
</TEXT>
