<HEADLINE>
FT  18 FEB 92 / Steep rise in complaints over life assurance sales
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SHARP PRACTICE among life assurance sales agents is rising steeply,
according to Lautro, the self-regulatory body that oversees the industry.
In its annual report on monitoring and enforcement in the year to June 1991,
Lautro recorded a big increase in consumer complaints, mostly about
over-selling and the sale of unsuitable products. Complaints rose 77 per
cent to more than 4,000.
Lautro has changed some membership rules to curb excesses. Some of the
increase in complaints could reflect growing consumer awareness of the
regulatory body, Lautro said, but there was little doubt that sharp practice
had increased.
For instance, Lautro found a majority of life assurance companies that rely
heavily on tied sales agents - roughly half of all life companies  - 'have
serious compliance shortcomings'.
The companies have typically failed to comply with rules on checking
references, curbing the enthusiasm of new sales agents or providing proper
training. Failure to comply with these rules is closely linked to
mis-selling.
Tied agents are those not employed directly by life assurance companies but
who sell the products of one company exclusively and receive commission for
each policy they sell. Typically, insurance companies pay far higher
commissions to tied agents than to independent financial advisers who sell
the best product of a group of companies.
A recent study by the Securities and Investments Board found that up to 44
per cent of policies sold by tied agents were cancelled within the first two
years, an indication that the policy was mis-sold in the first place.
Lautro also found a large increase in the number of investors questioning
the advice they had received on personal pensions, particularly where sales
agents had urged the transfer out of attractive occupational pension schemes
into less attractive private ones.
'Company representatives too often fail to make a sufficiently detailed
realistic or objective analysis of the relative merits of transferring their
prospective investors to a personal pension or leaving them in their
occupational scheme,' Lautro said in its report.
It said the number of complaints about personal pensions could understate
the extent of the problem. Pensions generally are so complex that few people
know whether they have been misled.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
