<HEADLINE>
FT  18 FEB 92 / US funds job plan for nuclear experts in Russia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Foreign Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE US is to provide Dollars 25m (Pounds 14m) for an internationally
sponsored 'job centre' in Russia for nuclear scientists from the former
Soviet Union.
Mr James Baker, US secretary of state, said yesterday, after talks with
President Boris Yeltsin in Moscow, that Washington would contribute the
money to discourage top scientists from selling their skills abroad. The
scientists earn about Rbs1,200 a month.
A statement issued with Russia and Germany said the centre would be 'a
clearing house for developing, selecting, funding and monitoring projects
that would be carried out . . . at facilities located in the Russian
Federation and other interested Commonwealth states.' The scientists would
'redirect their talents to non-military endeavours'.
The US also offered to supply 25 special rail containers to transport
nuclear warheads to Russia from other republics.
The European Community immediately gave its backing to the International
Science and Technology Centre. Mr Frans Andriessen, the EC external affairs
commissioner, told foreign ministers of the Twelve in Lisbon that the
Community had earmarked Ecu50m (Pounds 35.6m) of 1991 technical aid for
nuclear safety in the Commonwealth of Independent States, and some of this
could be used to fund the nuclear job centre.
Professor V. Mikhailov, head of the former Soviet Union's military nuclear
programme, said last month that 100,000 people were employed making atomic
weapons. Between 2,000 and 3,000 possessed key nuclear secrets. Such experts
are banned from leaving the country, but the west still fears that military
spending cuts will turn them into atomic mercenaries.
Prof Mikhailov said skilled Russians were needed to dismantle the redundant
nuclear weapons; without them, the country could be turned into 'one big
Chernobyl'.
The US and Russia agreed to keep working on further cuts in strategic
nuclear weapons. Mr Yeltsin said he expected the matters being discussed
would be ready for a formal agreement at a summit with President Bush in
July.
