</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MISAWA, a Japanese property group, is to take a 13 per cent stake in
Ishihara Construction, an ailing contractor, for an undisclosed sum, Reuter
reports from Tokyo.
Misawa's purchase of 5.42m Ishihara shares aims to help reconstruct
Ishihara, which is in financial trouble because it guaranteed a large debt
for steel-frame maker Kyowa, a company at the heart of a political scandal.
Kyowa was declared bankrupt last May with debts of about Y200bn (Dollars
1.6bn).
Ishihara had guaranteed Y21bn of Kyowa's outstanding debt and has been
obliged to put up three Japanese properties and another in Malaysia as
collateral for the debt. The contractor had guaranteed loans totalling
Y4.6bn for Ohira Sangyo, a failed property group.
'We consider this purchase an investment in the future of Ishihara, which
has good engineers and a good reputation for high-rise building
construction,' Misawa said.
Ishihara is listed on the Tokyo stock exchange's second section. Misawa is
the main shareholder of Misawa Homes, the Japanese home builder.
