<HEADLINE>
FT  18 FEB 92 / International Company News: New orders at MAN fall by 14% in
first half
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW FISHER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NEW orders at MAN, the German engineering group, fell by 14 per cent to
DM8.6bn (Dollars 5.4bn) in the six months to December as a result of the
world economic slowdown and the slackening of Germany's own post-unification
jump in demand.
But the group still expects turnover and profits to be maintained for the
whole of this year (to June 1992) due to a high backlog in orders.
MAN, whose products include trucks, printing equipment, diesel engines and
industrial plant, said new domestic orders declined by 12 per cent and those
from abroad by 16 per cent.
Turnover in the July-December period - the financial year runs to end-June -
was down by 0.5 per cent to DM8.4bn; while domestic sales were 21 per cent
higher, foreign sales fell by 13 per cent.
The best performance came from MAN Nutzfahrzeuge, the commercial vehicle
subsidiary, which produced a rise of 14 per cent in sales to DM3.8bn. This
unit has benefited considerably from demand connected with the supplying and
rebuilding of the east German economy. Truck sales in other markets also
advanced.
By contrast, MAN Roland, the printing equipment manufacturer, suffered a 7
per cent drop in sales to DM1.2bn. MAN Roland recently announced plans to
shed around 750 workers as a result of declining orders. The total number of
MAN group employees went down by 900 people in the July-December period to
63,700.
Because of its continuing high backlog of orders, worth DM18.4bn at
end-December, a 1 per cent rise on the previous year, MAN still expects
turnover to show an overall rise in the 1991-92 financial year.
It said profits should be roughly unchanged. Last year, MAN increased its
net profits by 24 per cent to DM406m on turnover which was 16 per cent
higher at DM19bn.
</TEXT>
