FT  18 FEB 92 / Production increase at Honda seen
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A FIRM prediction that Honda will move fairly quickly to production of
200,000 cars a year at its Pounds 300m plant now under construction at
Swindon, Wiltshire - twice the officially-declared capacity - was made
yesterday by Professor Garel Rhys, a senior motor industry economist.
The forecast was based on the size of component purchases Honda has
indicated it will make in Europe, and on the economy of scale disadvantage
the plant would otherwise face in comparison with Japanese competitors in
the UK.
Prof Rhys, of Cardiff Business School, said Honda envisages spending between
Pounds 600m and Pounds 800m a year in full production. Toyota was planning
spending of about Pounds 700m at its 200,000-cars-a-year plant due to come
on stream in Burnaston, Derbyshire, and Nissan Pounds 850m at the
300,000-car-a-year level in Sunderland. Because of this, said Prof Rhys, it
was 'virtually inconceivable' that Honda would not move to at least 200,000
units annually, perhaps by the mid-90s.
