<HEADLINE>
FT  18 FEB 92 / Big energy users seek nuclear cap
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIET SYCHRAVA
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LARGE ELECTRICITY consumers will today ask Mr John Wakeham, the energy
secretary, to cut their bills by capping the subsidy they pay to the nuclear
industry.
A group of large customers, including Blue Circle Cement and United
Engineering Steel, has already threatened to stop paying the subsidy, which
represents 11 per cent of their electricity bills, in April. According to
the Major Energy Users Council, some large customers may also refuse to pay
the increase in the energy charge, which represents the bulk of their
electricity bill.
The council is meeting Mr Wakeham in the first of a series of talks intended
to resolve the row over the increase in large consumers' bills since the
electricity industry was privatised in 1990.
Council representatives said yesterday that capping the subsidy was one way
of getting bills down to the level enjoyed by their European competitors.
Another option was to cut the charges levied by the National Grid Company.
The large users indicated that refusing to pay the nuclear levy was
primarily a tactic to show they believed that the government, which collects
the levy, was to blame for their high bills, rather than the electricity
generators.
One council representative said the government's decision to create only two
electricity generators in England and Wales - National Power and PowerGen -
with too much market share, had left large users unable to negotiate
competitive prices. 'We all know competition will emerge but the transition
needs to be smoothed, and that is the government's responsibility,' he said.
Several council members also accused Professor Stephen Littlechild, the
electricity regulator, of failing to refer the generators to the Monopolies
and Mergers Commission because a referral would be damaging to the
government in the approach to the election.
Mr Peter Rost, council chairman, said Prof Littlechild had suggested
alternative ways of helping the large users, including capping the nuclear
levy.
But the council members said the group was disturbed that the price at which
Nuclear Electric was offering power - about 2.6p a unit - was being used by
National Power and PowerGen as a benchmark to determine the price at which
they would sell electricity to large users.
</TEXT>
