FT  18 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics in Brief: Welcome for new EC deal
with Efta
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S financial-services sector should be one of the main beneficiaries
from the new agreement between the European Community and the European Free
Trade Association (Efta), Mr Tim Sainsbury, trade minister, told the Commons
last night, Ivor Owen writes.
He envisaged that the agreement would lead to 'significant economic gains'
for British industry and for British consumers.
Mr Sainsbury said there would be free movement of capital, services, goods
and people in the single market.
There would be a mutual recognition of professional qualifications, covering
accountants as well as other specialists, throughout the area.
Welcoming the agreement from the Opposition front bench, Ms Joyce Quin
emphasised that the parties to the new agreement should seek to promote
world trade as a whole and seek to dispel ideas of a 'fortress Europe'.
She hoped that the agreement would be used to strengthen economically
deprived regions in Britain and other countries.
Mr Kenneth Warren (C Hastings and Rye), chairman of the cross-party trade
and industry select committee, urged the European parliament not to look for
ways of obstructing the agreement.
*****
PROPERTY THEFTS: Mr John MacGregor, lord president of the council, said
yesterday there had been a considerable reduction since Christmas in the
number of reported thefts of MPs' property.
Responding to a question from Ms Alice Mahon, the Labour MP for Halifax, he
said he had not discussed the thefts with the security services but had seen
no evidence to support recent allegations.
Ms Mahon asked whether Mr MacGregor was satisfied the security services were
not trying to smear Opposition MPs.
*****
HUNG PARLIAMENT: Mr Paddy Ashdown, Liberal Democrat leader, said yesterday
that Labour or the Tories should try to form a coalition government with
minority parties in the event of a hung parliament, rather than making a
'fast dash' to a second contest.
