<HEADLINE>
FT  18 FEB 92 / Waldegrave announces HIV compensation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GOVERNMENT compensation for people infected with HIV, the virus that can
lead to Aids, during National Health Service blood transfusions and tissue
transfers, was announced yesterday by Mr William Waldegrave, the health
secretary.
The package, which will cost about Pounds 12m, follows a Pounds 42m scheme
announced in November 1990 to help haemophiliacs who suffered in the same
way. There were 74 reports at the end of December of HIV infection in people
who had blood transfusions or tissue transfers. The maximum payment will be
Pounds 80,500.
The circumstances of each infected transfusion or tissue recipient will be
considered individually to establish that the treatment was the source of
their infection.
A panel of experts, chaired by Mr Benet Hytner QC, will be set up to
consider cases where necessary.
Payments will be made as soon as possible.
Mr Waldegrave said the government did not accept the argument for a general
scheme of 'no fault' compensation for medical accidents, but ministers had
decided to treat patients infected with HIV as a special case.
Labour welcomed the change in the government's position, although it
criticised the delay in reaching the decision. Mr Neil Kinnock, the Labour
leader, suggested the shift 'may well have more to do with the approaching
election than with the existing injustice to people tragically and
accidentally infected with HIV'.
The amounts of payments to be made are Pounds 41,500 for each infant, Pounds
43,500 each for single adults, Pounds 52,000 for each married adult without
dependent children and Pounds 80,500 each for infected people with dependent
children.
These sums comprise the variable amounts paid to HIV infected haemophiliacs
following the settlement of litigation, and the payments of Pounds 20,000 to
each HIV infected haemophiliac which were announced on November 23 1989.
Mrs Margaret Jay, director of the National Aids Trust, said: 'The
government's decision is welcome, but late. It could have saved long months
of unnecessary hardship by making this announcement earlier.'
</TEXT>
