<HEADLINE>
FT  18 FEB 92 / Big trade deficits 'threaten' Emu
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S progress towards European economic and monetary union might be
jeopardised by large current account deficits, a group of private-sector
economists warned yesterday in a report which reflects Labour party
thinking.
The economists say the big import bills expected as Britain moves out of
recession will mean a rise by 1996 in the current account deficit, possibly
to 3.2 per cent of gross domestic product.
Such large deficits could damage investor confidence and hinder efforts to
reduce UK inflation and interest rates ahead of Emu, which Britain has
indicated it might join towards the end of the century.
The analysis comes from economists at the National Institute of Economic and
Social Research, London Business School, Oxford Economic Forecasting and
Warwick University. It was co-ordinated by Mr Jeremy Bray, the Labour
spokesman on science and technology, who also has an interest in economic
modelling.
The Treasury disputed the conclusions, saying it was difficult to look far
enough ahead to predict likely deficits in the late 1990s. There was 'no
evidence' to suggest Britain would find it difficult to finance any deficits
that arose.
The economists say the current account deficit - which fell to Pounds 5.8bn
last year after Pounds 15.2bn in 1990 - reflects structural difficulties in
the economy which will become more apparent during the expected upturn.
It argues that as imports rise due to increased demand, any matching rise in
exports will be insufficient to prevent a large increase in the de-ficit.
Over the period to 1996 the deficit will increase to between 1.5 per cent
and 2 per cent of total UK output, from about 1 per cent last year,
according to the group.
In a 'worst case' - assuming exports rise only slowly with a large jump in
imports - the deficit could reach 3.2 per cent of output.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
