<HEADLINE>
FT  18 FEB 92 / (CORRECTED) Companies hit back over river pollution
criticisms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON and NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Correction (published 19th February 1992) appended to this article.
BRITAIN'S biggest companies yesterday insisted that they were taking their
environmental responsibilities seriously, in spite of a report which said 27
of them exceeded limits for discharging effluent into rivers.
The 27, among the largest 50 companies in the FT-A All-Share index, were
listed in a report by the Ethical Investment Research Service (Eiris), based
on records for the last three years from the National Rivers Authority and
the River Purification Boards in Scotland. The incidence varies from
exceeding limits once in the last three years to 35 times in the last year.
The companies named are not necessarily the worst polluters, but they are
the largest companies responsible for pollution.
The reaction of most companies was that given their size, the number of
incidents was lower than might be expected.
Several said the breaches referred to by Eiris occurred up to three years
ago, and that measures were being taken to ensure they were not repeated.
Guinness, for example, has had problems with nine of its 31 malt whisky
distilleries in Scotland. Unlike the rest, these nine were discharging
treated effluent directly into rivers.
Since 1990 Guinness has implemented a Pounds 2m programme to install
treatment plants to bring discharges within agreed levels.
Courtaulds is listed as exceeding discharge consents only once in the last
three years. In June 1989 a fractured water main at the acetates factory at
Spondon in Derbyshire led to acetile acid being discharged from the cooling
system into the river Derwent.
The company said: 'Acetile acid reacts in water. It takes out the oxygen,
and some fish were suffocated, but it did not cause any long-term damage.'
Courtaulds said systems had been put into operation to prevent similar
incidents.
Cadbury Schweppes said the rivers authority had recorded four cases of
discharge limits being exceeded at its Bournville, Birmingham plant in 1989.
But improvements in monitoring and control had prevented any recurrence of
the problem in 1990 or 1991.
Grand Metropolitan said some infringements had occurred at two Express
Dairies plants, which were sold to Northern Foods in November last year.
Controls had been improved to ensure the plants met their discharge
standards. One had since won an environmental award.
Other problems had occurred at the Auchroisk distillery in Moray, but
GrandMet said the distillery, built in 1974, had tighter permitted discharge
levels than older plants. The company is spending Pounds 250,000 on a
treatment plant to ensure that it meets the more stringent standards by
April.
BP said the Eiris comments were 'perfectly valid', adding that it was
working to reduce water pollution. It is spending Pounds 37m at the
Grangemouth refinery on the Forth on a water effluent treatment plant which
should be in operation by the end of 1993.
Each of BP's three main operating companies, covering oil, exploration and
chemicals, has a body supervising environmental control.
Many of the companies named by Eiris including GEC, Cadbury Schweppes and
Hanson, admitted that they had no central monitoring system or register of
pollution problems, but said that subsidiaries had their own environmental
units.
Correction (published 19th February 1992).
IN a report on water pollution published in yesterday's Financial Times it
was stated that General Electric Company had no central monitoring system or
register of pollution problems. In fact, GEC has a central register of
pollution problems and a group adviser on safety and the environment.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
