<HEADLINE>
FT  18 FEB 92 / (CORRECTED) Spar withdraws Italian wines
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Correction (published 12th February 1992) appended to this article.
SPAR, the grocery chain, yesterday withdrew two own-label brands of Italian
wine from its shelves after contamination fears.
The Valpolicella and Soave wines came from the same supplier as Pinot Grigio
and Merlot wines recalled by Marks and Spencer after fungicide was found in
the drinks.
Gateway, the food retailer, said it had withdrawn one of its Italian white
wines, Pinot Bianco del Zenato, which came from the same Italian supplier.
Correction (published 12th February 1992).
IN some editions of yesterday's issue, it was stated that Gateway, the
supermarket chain, had withdrawn from sale one of its Italian white wines,
Pinot Bianco del Zenato. Gateway says that this was an error in its press
release and the wine withdrawn was in fact Pinot Bianco del Veneto. No
Zenato wines are involved in the recently reported withdrawals of wines
feared to be contaminated with fungicides.
</TEXT>
