<HEADLINE>
FT  17 FEB 92 / BR wheels in new promotion scheme
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ONE of the last outposts of Buggins' Turn
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
promotion on seniority alone - will disappear from British industry at the
end of next month.
Rail commuters may not immediately notice the difference but from March 29
nearly 30,000 British Rail station staff will be promoted on merit rather
than length of service.
Although the Buggins principle seems quaintly old-fashioned in the era of
performance-related pay it was considered a step forward by the rail unions
when they forced the private railway companies to concede the principle in
the early 1900s.
Mr Lawrie Harries of the transport union RMT said: 'In those days there was
a lot of nepotism and favouritism on the railways with managers picking
their blue-eyed boys regardless of merit.'
The union says it is no longer opposed to the principle of suitability as
opposed to seniority in selecting job candidates and has already conceded
the point for most other rail workers.
But some reservations remain about giving management complete discretion.
The introduction of an unpopular system of promotion assessment was one of
the causes of the 1989 London Underground strike, led by RMT.
Also, the union argues that because of the non-transferability of many rail
skills, such as train driving, long-serving staff should be compensated for
their limited options outside the rail industry by preference for promotion
within it.
The union-favoured compromise, which already applies to train drivers and
will probably now apply to station staff, is that seniority should determine
the order of applicants for promotion even if suitability will remain the
final test of whether someone gets the job.
RMT will today present a claim to BR for a substantial increase in pay and a
reduction in hours to 35 a week. Average earnings for hourly paid rail
workers are pounds 266 a week but that includes a large amount of overtime.
The national average of hours worked each week is 52.
Sell-off plans face further delay, Page 6
