<HEADLINE>
FT  17 FEB 92 / High-tech blitz on crime against business: Police cameras on
the ground and in a helicopter will monitor industrial sites
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A HELICOPTER-MOUNTED television camera, hydraulic barriers outside shops to
deter ram-raiders and the use of a computerised geographical information
system to analyse and predict crime are among measures proposed to reduce
the highest crime rate in the country.
Encrypted radios, infra-red detection equipment on a police helicopter and
the installation of closed-circuit television systems to monitor urban
centres and industrial areas are also proposed by the Northumbria police
force in a submission to the Home Office.
Mr John Stevens, chief constable of the Northumbria force, which covers Tyne
and Wear and Northumberland, said the force's area had the country's highest
crime rate per 1,000 population and per police officer.
The government has chosen Northumbria, Merseyside and West Yorkshire police
forces for its one-year Urban Crime Fund experiment, to start in April. Each
will receive about Pounds 3.6m for innovative measures involving local
communities in the fight against urban crime.
Mr Stevens who became chief constable after last September's riots in North
Shields and Newcastle upon Tyne, has pledged to make crime against business
a priority in his use of the urban fund money, to which the Northumbria
police authority is adding Pounds 1.2m.
'Business confidence has been affected by the riots and the amount of
crime,' he said last week at a Tyne and Wear Chamber of Commerce seminar in
Newcastle.
He expects the private sector to help pay for closed-circuit television
(CCTV) in Newcastle city centre and North Shields.
He also plans to extend a Business Watch project in which co-ordinated
security on a Gateshead industrial estate, paid for by local companies, has
reduced burglaries.
Northumbria police believe the new, virtually crime-free Newcastle Business
Park, where the management charge covers CCTV, is a model of how to tackle
crime. Mr Stevens also plans a registration scheme for pub and club doormen.
His Urban Crime Fund proposals for Northumbria ally high technology to a
heightened police presence on problem housing estates where, he says, a hard
core of criminals are respected and emulated. Officers will target known
offenders, protect witnesses and stamp on harassment of local people and of
police officers and their families.
He proposes a 'drop-in' centre on one Sunderland estate, where police could
'interact' with residents. He has also recommended rewards for information.
The 3,500-strong Northumbria force has been pressing for extra manpower
since budget problems forced a cut of 116 officers this year. In November
last year the Home Office granted 27 extra posts, but the authority is
bidding for 80 more officers in 1992-93. Mr Stevens has switched many
officers to patrol duties, and under his crime-fund plans recruitment of
civilians will free a further 65 officers for front-line work.
Crime has been estimated to cost businesses nationally between Pounds 5bn
and Pounds 10bn a year, according to the Confederation of British Industry
and Crime Concern, a crime-prevention charity set up by the Home Office.
There is concern in Tyne and Wear that crime may deter investment and
job-creation. Mr Bob Tilmouth, chief executive of the Chamber of Commerce,
said: 'Anything which disrupts performance or endangers business survival
and confidence has to be tackled.'
</TEXT>
