FT  17 FEB 92 / Lilley cautious over Lloyd's
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS and SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR PETER Lilley, trade and industry secretary, indicated yesterday that he
does not intend to impose reform on Lloyd's in spite of the political storm
over allegations of malpractice at the insurance market.
About 25 MPs will today press for action to restore confidence in the
regulatory system at a lunch hosted by Lloyd's. One Tory MP said yesterday
that Mr David Coleridge, Lloyd's chairman, was a 'public relations disaster'
in spite of his strengths as an underwriter.
Suggestions that Lloyd's activities were being seriously disrupted as
members threatened legal action were dismissed as 'evident nonsense' by Mr
Alan Lord, chief executive.
The row follows allegations by Labour MPs last week. These included claims
that working Names were given preferential access to better-performing
syndicates - an allegation dismissed by Lloyd's. Names are the individuals
whose assets provide Lloyd's capital.
Mr Lilley, speaking on TV-am, said such allegations could be referred to
Lloyd's regulators, to the Serious Fraud Office or to the courts. All those
paths should be explored 'before we have to consider whether there's any
change in the legal structure that is required'.
He added: 'We are obviously keeping under close review - as we do - that
market and financial markets generally.'
Mr Richard Page, vice-chairman of the Tory backbench trade and industry
committee, said the government was right to give Lloyd's time to reform
itself. 'But the proviso is that they have got to get on and do it . . .
Time delays increase the pressure on the government to take some action,' he
said.
Mr Lord said it was not true that Lloyd's was running out of money.
