<HEADLINE>
FT  17 FEB 92 / UK News (Employment): ILO is criticised for being 'moribund'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE WORK of the International Labour Organisation, founded in 1919 to
establish an international code of workers rights, 'looks positively
moribund' compared with the European Community's Social Charter, according
to an analysis published today.
Professor Keith Ewing, professor of public law at King's College, University
of London, says in the new London-based magazine International Union Rights,
that the ILO's attempts to create an international code of rights 'have to
some extent run into the sands'.
He says: 'Although worldwide labour is on the defensive, very few really
significant conventions (ILO rulings) emerged in the 1980s to add to the
code.'
He adds that many of the most significant conventions have never been
ratified by some countries.
The US, for example, has never ratified conventions 87 on freedom of
association and 98 on the right to organise and collective bargaining. But
even where conventions have been ratified, the ILO has no way of forcing
governments to comply with their terms. 'The problems here have become acute
as more countries have chosen to deregulate labour law as a means of helping
to prevent further economic decline.'
The UK government has been repeatedly found in breach of convention 87 over
the banning of unions from the Government Communications Headquarters
(GCHQ).
'It has refused to comply and there is nothing that can be done to compel it
to do so,' says Prof Ewing.
According to the Trades Union Congress the British government will this year
receive the worst possible reprimand the ILO can deliver, a special mention
at the organisation's annual conference for 'grave and persistent' violation
of conventions.
Prof Ewing believes that the ILO should not be written off, adding that,
while the ILO condemned banning unions at GCHQ, the European Commission on
Human Rights did not. He also says that the ILO was an inspiration for those
drafting the EC Social Charter. But he concludes that a 'stronger
organisation is required with a greater influence on the nations throughout
the world'.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
</DOC>
