<HEADLINE>
FT  17 FEB 92 / University research income increases
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RESEARCH AND contract income generated by British universities is growing at
more than Pounds 100m a year, but their student-staff ratio is worsening,
according to figures published today by the Universities Statistical Record
(USR).
Between 1988-89 and 1989-90 universities' total income from research grants
and contracts grew by 20 per cent, from Pounds 629m to Pounds 752m.
Of that sum, income from overseas organisations - including the European
Community - increased by one third, with funds from research councils rising
23 per cent and those from UK-based charitable bodies increasing 18 per
cent.
Over the same year universities' total revenue grew by 14 per cent, from
Pounds 3.41bn to Pounds 3.89bn. Almost half came from direct government
grants, with 14 per cent from student fees and support grants, 7 per cent
from research councils and a similar proportion from residences and
catering.
Student numbers increased by 6 per cent over the year to 382,000, but the
number of full-time academic and academic-related staff grew only 3.7 per
cent, to 58,480 - evidence of a progressive increase in the student-staff
ratio, now about 12:1.
The USR also reports strong growth in continuing education. It says the
number of courses and student enrolments rose by more than 40 per cent in
the five years to 1990.
University Statistics 1989-90 Vol 3. USR, PO Box 130, Cheltenham,
Gloucestershire GL50 3SE. Pounds 11.25.
</TEXT>
