<HEADLINE>
FT  17 FEB 92 / BR sell-off plans face further delay
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CABINET ministers are preparing the ground for a further delay in
publication of plans for the privatisation of British Rail. The government
had previously hoped to release details before the general election.
Clashes between ministers over how the rail network should be restructured
seem unlikely to be resolved in time for a white paper before April 9 - the
most likely election date.
A senior minister said yesterday that the imminence of the election was
likely to mean that only broad proposals would appear in the Conservative
manifesto. The white paper would follow if the Tories were re-elected.
That would be at least the third delay for the white paper. When Mr John
Major, the prime minister, unveiled his Citizen's Charter last summer the
white paper was promised by the end of last year. This was subsequently
delayed until January and then to before the election.
The dispute has been caused by Mr Major's preference for reviving the
pre-war regional railway companies. This conflicts with the determination of
Mr Malcolm Rifkind, transport secretary, to keep intact the InterCity
service.
Mr Rifkind had hoped for agreement on a compromise that would have kept
InterCity in one piece and sold to a private operator, but with new regional
companies being able to run services on BR tracks.
</TEXT>
